GSEM factor analysis - theory-driven

AA, JP & AT

03 July, 2024

Factor structure underlying substance use: Alternative theoretical models

Here I’m going to test different alternative models in the full set of chromosomes, created with LDSC, without the index event bias-correction. I plot results for models with decent overall fit.

If the specific factors are fully orthogonal, model fit meets criteria only when relying on the four factors identified by EFA (best fit for first model). If we allow for correlations between the specific factors, theoretically-driven models based on substance or trait type also show good fit (best fit for …).

Bifactor models

Bifactor models are used to test if adding an extra general latent factor G (as in P for psychopathology) to the structure improves fit.

EFA-based

First, the 4-factor structure identified with EFA is tested. The model shows excellent fit, although not all indicators load significantly on their factor. F1 seems superfluous, it is almost as general as G. This argues for a S-1 model where the first factor is dropped.

load('data/mldsc_29May2023.14.TOT.RData')

bif <- '

G =~ NA*SMKCES + PACKYE + SMKDEP + CANDEP + COCDEP + OPIODEP + SMKAGE + ALCDEP + CANEV + CANFL + SMKINI + ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP

F1 =~ NA*SMKCES + PACKYE + SMKDEP + ALCDEP + ALCFRQ + COCDEP + CANEV + SMKINI + SMKAGE
F2 =~ NA*CANDEP + COCDEP + OPIODEP + SMKAGE
F3 =~ NA*ALCDEP + ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP 
F4 =~ NA*CANEV + CANFL + SMKINI

G~~1*G
F1~~1*F1
F2~~1*F2
F3~~1*F3
F4~~1*F4

G ~~ 0*F1 + 0*F2 + 0*F3 + 0*F4 

a>.001
CANEV~~a*CANEV

b>0.001
SMKAGE~~b*SMKAGE

c>-0.999
F1~~c*F2

d>-0.999
F1~~d*F4
'


#run the model
fit <- usermodel(ldscOut, estimation = "DWLS", model = bif, CFIcalc = TRUE)

Plot EFA-based bifactor model

semPlotModel_GSEM=function(gsem.object=GWISoutput , est.label="STD_All"){ 
      
       object=gsem.object$results
       object$free=0
       numb=1:length(which(object$op!="~~"))
       object$free[which(object$op!="~~")]=numb
       varNames <- lavaanNames(object, type = "ov")
       factNames <- lavaanNames(object, type = "lv")
       factNames <- factNames[!factNames %in% varNames]
       n <- length(varNames)
       k <- length(factNames)
       if (is.null(object$label)) 
         object$label <- rep("", nrow(object))
       semModel <- new("semPlotModel")
       object$est <- object[,est.label]
       if (is.null(object$group)) 
         object$group <- ""
       semModel@Pars <- data.frame(label = object$label, lhs = ifelse(object$op == 
                                                                        "~" | object$op == "~1", object$rhs, object$lhs), edge = "--", 
                                   rhs = ifelse(object$op == "~" | object$op == "~1", object$lhs, 
                                                object$rhs), est = object$est, std = NA, group = object$group, 
                                   fixed = object$free==0, par = object$free, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
       semModel@Pars$edge[object$op == "~~"] <- "<->"
       semModel@Pars$edge[object$op == "~*~"] <- "<->"
       semModel@Pars$edge[object$op == "~"] <- "~>"
       semModel@Pars$edge[object$op == "=~"] <- "->"
       semModel@Pars$edge[object$op == "~1"] <- "int"
       semModel@Pars$edge[grepl("\\|", object$op)] <- "|"
       semModel@Thresholds <- semModel@Pars[grepl("\\|", semModel@Pars$edge), 
                                            -(3:4)]
       semModel@Pars <- semModel@Pars[!object$op %in% c(":=", "<", 
                                                        ">", "==", "|", "<", ">"), ]
       semModel@Vars <- data.frame(name = c(varNames, factNames), 
                                   manifest = c(varNames, factNames) %in% varNames, exogenous = NA, 
                                   stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
       semModel@ObsCovs <- list()
       semModel@ImpCovs <- list()
       semModel@Computed <- FALSE
       semModel@Original <- list(object)
       return(semModel)
       
}

S-1 bifactor

Instead, we test an S-1 bifactor model. The fit is still very good, though it is unclear why cannabis initiation and alcohol frequency load negatively on G and the loading of cannabis frequency on G is not significant.

bif <- 'G =~ NA*SMKCES + PACKYE + SMKDEP + CANDEP + COCDEP + OPIODEP + SMKAGE + ALCDEP + CANEV + CANFL + SMKINI + ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP

F2 =~ NA*CANDEP + COCDEP + OPIODEP + SMKAGE
F3 =~ NA*ALCDEP + ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP 
F4 =~ NA*CANEV + CANFL + SMKINI

G~~1*G
F2~~1*F2
F3~~1*F3
F4~~1*F4

G ~~ 0*F2 + 0*F3 + 0*F4

a>.001
CANEV~~a*CANEV

b>.001
OPIODEP~~b*OPIODEP
'

Second-order factor

This next bifactor model is hierarchical, such that the general factor G is made up by the other specific factors. The correlation between the factors is forced through G, so they are orthogonal. It shows good fit, but the loading of cannabis initiation on F1 is negative, and F4 does not load significantly on G.

bif <- 'G =~ NA*F1 + F2 + F3 + F4

F1 =~ NA*SMKCES + PACKYE + SMKDEP + ALCDEP + ALCFRQ + COCDEP + CANEV + SMKINI + SMKAGE
F2 =~ NA*CANDEP + COCDEP + OPIODEP + SMKAGE
F3 =~ NA*ALCDEP + ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP 
F4 =~ NA*CANEV + CANFL + SMKINI

G~~1*G
F1~~1*F1
F2~~1*F2
F3~~1*F3
F4~~1*F4

G ~~ 0*F1 + 0*F2 + 0*F3 + 0*F4 
F1 ~~ 0*F2 + 0*F3 + 0*F4
F2 ~~ 0*F3 + 0*F4
F3 ~~ 0*F4

'

Theoretical models

We now move on to models that are not based on the original EFA but rather on what seems sensible at the face of it. We grouped by substance type as well as by trait type.

Correlated factors by substance

Here, we fit 4 factors split up by substance. We drop cocaine and opioid because they do not fit in the main factors. Although the loadings make perfect sense, the fit is poor.

cfa <- '
SMK =~ NA*PACKYE + SMKCES + SMKDEP + SMKAGE + SMKINI 
ALC =~ NA*ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP + ALCDEP 
CAN =~ NA*CANEV + CANFL + CANDEP 

SMK~~1*SMK
ALC~~1*ALC
CAN~~1*CAN

a>.001
ALCDEP~~a*ALCDEP
'

Bifactor by substance

Next, we add G to this model. It shows excellent fit. There is again a sig negative loading of ALCFRQ on G, and no sig loadings of smoking cessation, packyears, and dependence on the SMK factor. Note that the SMK factor is reversed, such that it has a positive loading of SMKAGE and a negative loading of SMKINI. This explains the negative correlation between the SMK and other factors. In this model, cocaine and opioid dependence have been dropped because they don’t fit in any factor.

bif <- 'G =~ NA*PACKYE + SMKCES + SMKDEP + SMKAGE + SMKINI + ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP + ALCDEP + CANEV + CANFL + CANDEP

SMK =~ NA*PACKYE + SMKCES + SMKDEP + SMKAGE + SMKINI 
ALC =~ NA*ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP + ALCDEP 
CAN =~ NA*CANEV + CANFL + CANDEP

G ~~ 0*SMK + 0*ALC + 0*CAN

G~~1*G
SMK~~1*SMK
ALC~~1*ALC
CAN~~1*CAN

b>.001
CANEV~~b*CANEV

c>.001
SMKINI~~c*SMKINI
'

S-1 by trait type

Again, we remove the first factor because it’s captured by G. This time the model is more sensible, because the first factor was initiation, which should be the better part of the signal in G. The dependence factor does not have significant indicators, otherwise the structure looks OK. The fit is not good.

CFA <- 'G =~ NA*SMKINI + SMKAGE + CANEV + PACKYE + ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP + CANFL + SMKDEP + ALCDEP + CANDEP + COCDEP + OPIODEP

Conclusion

The best fit is achieved for the models based on the 4-factor EFA solution, with similar fit for an S-1 and second-order model. For the theory-based models, only the standard bifactor models show good fit, and only if the specific factors are allowed to correlate. This is somewhat worrying, as bifactor models often inflate overall fit estimates. This caveat is confirmed by the sometimes shaky indicator loadings, although these were sometimes also observed in the non-bifactor solutions. Overall, it seems that the theory-based bifactor models can be used for follow-up analyses, but should not be over-interpreted as constituting the ‘true’ factor structure.
